/*! 
 * \page gstarted Getting Started

\if USER_GUIDE
This section describes how to download, build and install the TEVA-SPOT
Toolkit (SPOT) software. Further, we use a simple example to illustrate
how to run SPOT.

\section gStartedInstalling Installing SPOT
\else
\latexonly
\section*{Installing SPOT}
\endlatexonly
\endif

\if USER_GUIDE
\subsection gStartedInstallingWindows Windows
\else
\latexonly
\subsection*{Windows}
\endlatexonly
\endif

NOTE: these instructions will likely change once we have an automated installer.  In fact, these instructions may not be necessary at all!

The SPOT distribution for MS Windows is a gzip'd archive with executables and
scripts.  Although this can be extracted anywhere, it's convenient to extract it in a standard place, such as the root disk, or in "C:\Program Files".
Native MS Windows executables can be used in the DOS shell by configuring the MS Windows environment. For Windows NT, 2000 and XP, you will need to add a string such as
\verbatim
    ;C:\teva-spot_2.0\bin
\endverbatim
to the current setting for the PATH environment variable, which you
will find in the properties window of "My Computer" under the "Advanced"
tab. If you don't find a properties window at "My Computer", the same
tool may be found on the "Control Panel" at "System Properties".

Note that if you have sufficient privilege you might get a choice of
installing the settings either for the Current User or for System. The
latter is preferred if you want everybody to be able to run SPOT on
the machine. At this stage you may need to reboot your system to have the new setting take effect; you probably will not need to reboot
for XP.

Using SPOT in a DOS shell requires the additional installation of Python.  The latest Python release can be obtained at 
\htmlonly
<a href="http://www.python.org">http://www.python.org</a>
\endhtmlonly
\latexonly
\c http://www.python.org
\endlatexonly
.  Python is installed with a MSI installer that is easy to use.  To employ Python from a DOS shell requires an additional step: the PATH environmental variable needs to be edited to specify the location of the Python executable. This is the same process used to configure SPOT, but the Python MS Windows FAQ provides further details:
\htmlonly
<a href="http://www.python.org/doc/faq/windows.html">http://www.python.org/doc/faq/windows.html</a>.
\endhtmlonly
\latexonly
http://www.python.org/doc/faq/windows.html .
\endlatexonly


\if USER_GUIDE
\subsection gStartedInstallingUnix Unix
\else
\latexonly
\subsection*{Unix}
\endlatexonly
\endif

In Unix, a user can install SPOT executables from the tarball distribution.
The command
\verbatim
    gzcat teva-spot.tar.gz | tar xf -
\endverbatim
extracts the files from the tarball into a local subdirectory, such as \c teva-spot_2.0/bin. A user can setup the \c PATH environment variable to configure the command shell to use these executables. The details of this depend on the command shell. For example, if the SPOT files were extracted in the user's home
directory, then a BASH shell would be configured by adding the lines
\verbatim
    PATH=$PATH:$HOME/teva-spot_2.0/bin
    export PATH
\endverbatim
to the \c ~/.bashrc file.



\if USER_GUIDE
\section gStartedExecutables SPOT Executables
\else
\latexonly
\section*{SPOT Executables}
\endlatexonly
\endif

The following executables included in SPOT can be used from a command line:
<ul>

<li> \ref tevasimExecutable "tevasim" - A command to execute an ensemble of contamination incidents, using EPANET. This command builds a \c  TSO file that summarizes these simulation results in a compact manner.

<li> \ref tso2ImpactExecutable "tso2Impact" - A command that reads a \c TSO file and creates one or more \c IMPACT files that are used to formulate sensor placement problems.

<li> \ref scenarioAggrExecutable "scenarioAggr" - A command that reads an \c IMPACT file and creates an \c IMPACT file with fewer events, along with a file of event probabilities.

<li> \ref spExecutable "sp" - The SPOT solver interface for performing sensor placement, which uses data from \c IMPACT files.

<li> \ref evalsensorExecutable "evalsensor" - A command that reads in one or more sensor placements and summarizes their performance according to various metrics.

</ul>
A variety of other executables are provided with SPOT, many of which are used by \ref spExecutable "sp" to
perform sensor placement.


\if USER_GUIDE
\section gStartedExample A Simple Example
\else
\latexonly
\section*{A Simple Example}
\label{gstarted-example}
\endlatexonly
\endif

The following example illustrates the main steps required to (1) simulate  contamination incidents,  (2) compute contamination impacts, (3) perform sensor placement, and (4) evaluate a sensor placement. The data used in this example is available in the \c spot/examples/simple directory.  This example places sensors in EPANET example 3 (Net3), a small distribution system with 97 junctions.
\if USER_GUIDE
See Section \ref impacts
\else
See Section <b>Contamination Incidents and Impact Measures</b> 
of the TEVA-SPOT Toolkit User Guide
\endif
for a complete description of the objective measures supported by SPOT.

\if USER_GUIDE
\subsection gStarted1 Using tevasim
\else
\latexonly
\subsection*{Using tevasim}
\endlatexonly
\endif

The file \c spot/examples/simple/Net3.tsg defines an ensemble of contamination scenarios for Net3. 
Contamination incidents are simulated for all network junctions, one for each hour of the day, and each
contamination incident models an inject that continues for 24 hours.  The \c tevasim command uses EPANET to
perform these contaminant transport simulations, using the following command line:
\verbatim
    tevasim -tsg Net3.tsg -tso Net3.tso Net3.inp Net3.out
\endverbatim
This command generates three files: (a) Net3.tso, a binary file that contains the contamination transport data, (b) Net3.sdx, a binary file that provides an index into the TSO file, and (c) Net3.out, which provides a textual summary of the EPANET simulations.


\if USER_GUIDE
\subsection gStarted2 Using tso2Impact
\else
\latexonly
\subsection*{Using tso2Impact}
\endlatexonly
\endif

Next, the \c Net3.tso and \c Net3.sdx files can be used to compute one or more \c IMPACT files.  An \c IMPACT file summarizes the consequence of each contamination incident in a manner that facilitates optimization.
The \c tso2Impact command generates these files with the following command line:
\verbatim
    tso2Impact Net3 Net3.tso -mc -vc -td -nfd -ec -epanetin Net3.inp
\endverbatim
This command generates impact files for each of the five objectives specified: mass consumed (mc), volume consumed (vc), time to detection (td), number of failed detections (nfd) and extent of contamination (ec).  For each impact file (e.g. \c Net3_mc.impact ), a corresponding id file is generated to map the sensor placement ids back to the network junction labels (e.g. \c Net3_mc.impact.id ).


\if USER_GUIDE
\subsection gStarted3 Using sp
\else
\latexonly
\subsection*{Using sp}
\endlatexonly
\endif

The \c sp command is a Python script that coordinates the application of optimization solvers for sensor placement.  This script reads in one or more \c impact files, and computes a sensor placement.  For example, the command
\verbatim
    sp --path=../../bin --path=../../etc/mod --print-log --network="Net3" \
       --objective=mc --solver=heuristic --ub=ns,5 --seed=1234567
\endverbatim
 generates some solver output, ending with the following summary of the final solution:
\verbatim
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        22775
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            2 4 59 70 81
Sensor junctions:           15 35 203 219 253

Impact File:                /home/wehart/src/spot-limited/examples/simple/Net3_mc.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
Mean impact:                21781.9899
Lower quartile impact:      289.3540
Median impact:              1355.1400
Upper quartile impact:      9272.3900
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 144271.0000
TCE                 (  5%): 144276.3333
Max impact:                 144335.0000
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\endverbatim
Further, the sensors found by this optimizer are put into the \c Net3.sensors file.


\if USER_GUIDE
\subsection gStarted4 Using evalsensor
\else
\latexonly
\subsection*{Using evalsensor}
\endlatexonly
\endif

The final output provided by \c sp is actually generated by the \c evalsensor command.  However, this command can evaluate a sensor placement for a wide variety of different objectives.  For example, the command
\verbatim
    evalsensor --nodemap=Net3.nodemap Net3.sensors Net3_ec.impact \
               Net3_mc.impact Net3_nfd.impact
\endverbatim
will summarize the solution in the \c Net3.sensors file for the \c ec, \c mc and \c nfd impact measures:
\verbatim
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        22775
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            2 4 59 70 81
Sensor junctions:           15 35 203 219 253

Impact File:                Net3_ec.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
Mean impact:                21082.9924
Lower quartile impact:      3050.0000
Median impact:              11830.0000
Upper quartile impact:      32761.9000
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 81586.8000
TCE                 (  5%): 93102.0250
Max impact:                 103746.0000

Impact File:                Net3_mc.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
