\if USER_GUIDE

\section gStartedDownload Downloading and Building SPOT Source Code (FOR DEVELOPERS)

The SPOT software is split into two codes: the SPOT software that is
distributed with an open-source license, and the SPOT-Limited software
that contains health impacts assessment software that is not freely
distributed.
The SPOT software can be downloaded directly from the University of Cincinnati
subversion repository using the following command line:
\verbatim
    svn checkout http://engcvs.uc.edu/repos/TEVA/spot/trunk spot
\endverbatim
Similarly, the SPOT-Limited software can be downloaded from the Argonne subversion repository with:
\verbatim
    svn checkout https://tevasvn.dis.anl.gov/TEVA/spot-limited/trunk spot-limited
\endverbatim
Note that user-accounts are needed to access these software repositories.


The SPOT software can be compiled on UNIX systems within a standard Unix shell. SPOT can also be compiled in a similar way on Windows within the Cygwin shell application. After checking out SPOT, 
move into the \c spot directory and run the setup script:
\verbatim
    cd spot
    ./setup configure build
\endverbatim
The \c setup script automates much of the setup activity
associated with building SPOT on various
hardware platforms.  This script recursively configures SPOT for the specific characteristics of the hardware platform, and it then
generates the SPOT executables and libraries.

Several output files can be viewed to assess whether the \c setup script 
worked properly:
<ol>

<li> spot/test/config.out - the logfile for the configuration process

<li> spot/test/config.xml - a summary of errors and warnings from the \c config.out file 

<li> spot/test/build.out - the logfile for the build process 

<li> spot/test/build.xml - a summary of errors and warnings from the \c build.out file 

</ol>

The executables built within the Cygwin shell can only run within this shell. However, SPOT can be configured to build "native" Windows executables, which can run in a DOS shell:
\verbatim
    cd spot
    ./setup configure --with-compiler=mingw build
\endverbatim

\endif

*/
